<p class="lede">I bought the watch because I couldn't stop thinking about it. A 1960s Nivada Grenchen Antarctic, with a dial that had turned from white to a warm cream over sixty years — the Japanese call this <em>yaketsuki</em>, the beautiful aging that happens when something has been lived with.</p>

<h2>Time blindness</h2>

<p>There's a condition — not officially, not in any manual — called time blindness. It's the inability to feel time passing. Not in the philosophical sense that occupies German professors. In the practical sense: you sit down to work, and when you look up, four hours have vanished. You consistently underestimate how long things take. You are perpetually, genuinely surprised that it's already Thursday.</p>

<p>I have this. I've had it my whole life.<sup class="footnote-ref" id="fnref-1"><a href="#fn-1">1</a></sup> And for most of that life, I compensated with systems — calendars, alarms, the gentle tyranny of other people's expectations. Moving to Copenhagen made it worse, or perhaps just more visible. When you immigrate, you lose the ambient time-keeping of familiarity.</p>

