<h2>What remains</h2>

<p>The Wanderer was Nivada Grenchen's attempt at a tool watch for people who moved between time zones. It had an inner rotating bezel — you could track a second time zone by turning the ring. This was 1960s practicality: if you're flying between Zurich and New York, you want to know what time it is in both places without doing arithmetic.</p>

<p>Sixty years later, I don't need that feature. My phone handles time zones. What I need is something more basic: a physical reminder that time is passing.<sup class="footnote-ref" id="fnref-2"><a href="#fn-2">2</a></sup></p>

<figure style="max-width: 55%;">
  <div style="aspect-ratio: 1/1; background: #2e2e4a; border-radius: 2px; width: 100%;"></div>
  <figcaption>Detail of the inner rotating bezel. The second timezone markings have faded unevenly.</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>This is the paradox of the immigrant's relationship to objects. You leave a country and you leave most of your things. The few objects that travel with you take on outsized significance — they become anchors in a life that's otherwise been unmoored and rebuilt.</p>

<p>There's a Japanese concept — <em>mono no aware</em><sup class="footnote-ref" id="fnref-3"><a href="#fn-3">3</a></sup> — that translates roughly as 'the pathos of things.' It's the bittersweet awareness that everything is transient. The cherry blossom is beautiful precisely because it falls.</p>

